Anyway, I’m finally starting ADHD meds in a couple of weeks, I’m no longer in shutdown (I don’t think). And there is supposed to be an article coming out about my ADHD and freelance illustration career with The Arena but I’ve been a puddle of tears for the past month. Soon!

This all got so bad at the beginning of 2020 that I would regularly have to walk out of the studio and go for walks, because my brain was so overstimulated it just froze. I’m convinced it’s the reason my old US agent dropped me (a story for another day).

I hyper fixate on almost everything, so the second things are sent off, you can bet your bottom dollar my brain hasn’t switched off from work, in fact, most of the time I am constantly circling back to it.

… in my head, they’re taking days and my schedule is too full and I meltdown. It’s like every single project or round within a project, I forget what I’m capable of, and having to build up your confidence per project/round, is quite frankly, exhausting.

I have almost no part of me, that can prioritise a task, or understand that sending an email isn’t as big of a deal as getting sketches done or finals. I find understanding time impossible, so even though my agent KNOWS I am capable of sketches in a couple of hours…

I had no idea this is how I felt, until my body shut down & I’ve started to recover & had time to reflect. ADHD doesn’t help anything either, I’m constantly overwhelmed, overstimulated, over exasperated. I don’t think people without ADHD understand HOW hard life feels.

This happened to me last August too, but nowhere near on the scale it has done this past month. Every email I got through, I cried. Every justified bit of feedback or correction I got, felt catastrophic. And I think I’d had enough. I needed distance.

I started resenting work because it felt too big of a stressor and I wasn’t getting any of the rest or recovery time I needed. And I think it reached breaking point & I snapped & that’s why I’ve spent almost 3 weeks in bed, asleep.

… because it couldn’t possibly take anymore. I’ve been working on long term projects since around June, that are demanding & the biggest of my career & I’m still working on them now. I worked through them during covid, post covid, post vaccine after bad reaction.
BURNOUT & WORK & ADHD; I’m seeing so many people talk about exhaustion & dip in MH at the moment, I am genuinely beginning to believe my body forced me to shut down…

- What I earn now is higher than I ever thought I could on illo, and it's not even gr8, lol. But I'm happy.
- Also can I just say - and this is not same for anyone - getting agent rep has been essentially in earning more, for me.

- I was the higher earner in my relationship last year, that has now changed, but we've always been equals in terms of rent & bills etc.
- Saying that applying for a mortgage, I was basically void in all discussions even though my salary last year was UKs "average salary"

- I got a term grant that balanced out my commissions 
- I only started earning enough (in my eyes) to go full time, without rent breaks, without MA, without part time jobs, last year - 4th year freelancing.
- This is mostly because I save to fuck, otherwise it wouldn't work

Doing the MA did exactly what I wanted. When I first moved to Bristol we moved in with Dans parents for 3 months, £100 a month, essentially another rent break.
- I did full time education alongside commissions, moved into own flat - expenses so high because BIG CITY LIFE

- Primary school hours & no chip shop meant I could do commissions after 3pm on weekdays, still not earning enough to full time
- I applied for an MA purely to be funded to live, not bc I had 100% interest & thought "it would be easy" - I was wrong, it was hard and a lot, BUT

- I think choosing not to move to a city was essential in my savings & ability to part time illo & part time chip shop. I had enough money to get by.
- When I was home for 3 months, I did an artist residency, my first rent break, mum didn't charge me

or getting any jobs of worth.
- Eventually felt like I was earning enough to part time illo, part time chip ship, but only bc my life in falmouth was so cheap, my rent was nothing compared to big city rent 
- I didn't move back home until 2yrs after graduating & only for 3 months

- Worked 2 jobs, ASDA & Chip Shop
- Continued with just Chip Shop at 40hrs moving from houseshare to houseshare in the tiniest rooms in falmouth - lowest costing room I found was £275pcm, incred but fucking awful living environments

The UK & it’s MH services are a joke, and my brother is only the tip of a ginormous iceberg. I watched him & Matt follow a similar route for years, and sadly only one of them came out the other end. I AM JUST SO MAD AND SO FED UP I WANT MY BROTHER TO LIVE A FULFILLING LIFE.

This has been an uphill battle since about 2014. The shit I’ve seen him go through, the shit we’ve collectively had to go through as a family. The fact I am now having to analyse his behaviour from a child & write it up  - in the hope - to be taken seriously. I’m exhausted.

This was the only way we got taken seriously by a psychiatrist. He got put on anti psychotic meds, and for the first time in about 5 years functioned like the same brother I grew up with. They’ve taken him off the meds, haven’t explored other options & he’s regressed massively

Having to take a day away from work because, yet again, my brother has been failed miserably by MH services. The last time it got this bad was in around 17/18 where I essentially had to write up a psychological review/report to summarise his behaviour

@peterandallen @SweatyEskimo @BenIllustrator @TheIlloSurvey @timeasley It's wonderful that we are generally nice, and welcoming and I'm not trying to downplay that whatsoever. But being nice as a community doesn't make way for those who are under represented. I know there was no malice in that 35%, but I also think there is ignorance behind it.

@peterandallen @SweatyEskimo @BenIllustrator @TheIlloSurvey @timeasley I was speaking to all three year groups, who had rarely given thought to what I was telling them - I even had lecturers coming up to me and saying it is something they had never even considered, and these are the people teaching soon to be industry illustrators.

@peterandallen @SweatyEskimo @BenIllustrator @TheIlloSurvey @timeasley I am also aware that fundamentally, there are important pieces missing within our current educational system. In the past when I have gone to universities to talk, and discuss representation & diversity as best I can from my POV ...

@peterandallen @SweatyEskimo @BenIllustrator @TheIlloSurvey @timeasley We are all learning, and I am fully aware of the fact that my experience, as a white female who was privileged enough to go to art school can not be compared to those who have really suffered unfair representation within this industry.
